ecords\":[{\"date\":\"2026-05-28\",\"patient_self_report\":\"\\u7528\\u836f 1 \\u5929\\u540e\\u51fa\\u73b0\\u5fc3\\u60b8\\uff0c\\u81ea\\u884c\\u505c\\u836f\",\"prescriptions\":[{\"dose\":\"0.4g\",\"duration_days\":2,\"frequency\":\"qd\",\"generic_name\":\"\\u83ab\\u897f\\u6c99\\u661f\\u6c2f\\u5316\\u94a0\\u6ce8\\u5c04\\u6db2\",\"route\":\"IV-drip\"},{\"diluent\":\"0.9%\\u6c2f\\u5316\\u94a0\\u6ce8\\u5c04\\u6db2 250ml\",\"dose\":\"0.5g\",\"duration_days\":2,\"frequency\":\"qd\",\"generic_name\":\"\\u963f\\u5947\\u9709\\u7d20\",\"route\":\"IV-drip\"}],\"source\":\"\\u5916\\u9662\\uff08XX\\u793e\\u533a\\u536b\\u751f\\u670d\\u52a1\\u4e2d\\u5fc3\\uff09\"}],\"renal_function\":{\"crcl\":105,\"dialysis\":false,\"egfr\":98},\"sex\":\"female\",\"vitals\":{\"blood_pressure\":\"118/74\",\"pulse_bpm\":96,\"respiration_per_min\":20,\"spo2_percent\":98,\"temperature_c\":38.2},\"weight_kg\":58}","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to C:\\Users\\<USER>\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\his-cpoe-20260531-145628-D60mGH","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-73a83f40-4d73-93b8-9ee4-aad3c4837ca8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"auto","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the patient data:\n\n**Patient:**\n- 32-year-old female, 58kg, 162cm\n- No allergies\n- No comorbidities\n- No current medications (stopped the previous ones)\n- Pregnancy: none\n- Renal function: normal (eGFR 98, CrCl 105, no dialysis)\n- Hepatic function: normal\n\n**Chief complaint:** 咳嗽咽痛 4 天，外院已开药\n\n**Present illness:** 4 days ago developed sore throat, cough with small amount white sputum, intermittent low fever (max 38.2°C). 2 days ago went to a community clinic, got IV drip prescription (moxifloxacin + azithromycin) for 2 days. After 1 day of use, patient felt no significant improvement and experienced palpitations/discomfort, stopped medication on their own and came to our hospital.\n\n**Diagnosis:** Acute upper respiratory tract infection (J06.9)\n\n**Physical exam:**\n- Conscious: alert\n- Throat: mild congestion, no pus, tonsils grade I enlargement\n- Lung auscultation: normal breath sounds, no rales\n- Lymph nodes: no enlargement\n\n**Labs:**\n- WBC: 6.8 (normal, ref 3.5-9.5)\n- N%: 58 (normal, ref 40-75)\n- CRP: 8.4 (normal, ref <10)\n\n**Vitals:**\n- BP: 118/74\n- Pulse: 96 bpm\n- Temp: 38.2°C\n- SpO2: 98%\n- RR: 20/min\n\n**Clinical analysis:**\n\nThis is a 32-year-old female with acute upper respiratory tract infection. Key points:\n\n1. **Likely viral etiology**: WBC normal (6.8), N% normal (58), CRP near normal (8.4), no pus on throat, mild congestion only, low-grade fever, white sputum (not purulent). These all suggest a viral URI rather than bacterial.\n\n2. **Previous inappropriate antibiotic therapy**: The community clinic gave moxifloxacin (fluoroquinolone) + azithromycin (macrolide) — a dual antibiotic combination that is:\n   - Overkill for likely viral URI\n   - Moxifloxacin has QT prolongation risk\n   - Azithromycin also has QT prolongation risk\n   - Combining two QT-prolonging drugs is dangerous, especially since the patient developed palpitations\n   - Moxifloxacin is a restricted antibiotic (should not be first-line for community URI)\n\n3. **Patient stopped due to palpitations**: This is likely related to the QT-prolonging effect of the combination. The patient correctly stopped.\n\n**My prescribing decision:**\n\nSince this appears to be a viral upper respiratory tract infection (normal WBC, normal CRP, no bacterial signs), antibiotics are NOT indicated. I should:\n\n1. **Not prescribe antibiotics** — viral URI doesn't need them\n2. **Symptomatic relief only**:\n   - For sore throat: perhaps a throat lozenge or local treatment\n   - For fever: antipyretic like ibuprofen or acetaminophen as needed\n   - For cough: consider a mild antitussive or expectorant if needed\n\nLet me check available drugs for symptomatic treatment. I need to look up:\n- Acetaminophen/paracetamol (对乙酰氨基酚) — for fever and sore throat\n- Possibly ibuprofen\n- Maybe some throat spray or lozenge\n\nLet me look up the drug information for a few options.\n\nActually, let me think about what drugs to prescribe:\n\n1. **对乙酰氨基酚 (Acetaminophen)** — for fever >38.5°C and sore throat, PRN. This is safe, NRDL A category, well-tolerated.\n\n2. Possibly a throat spray like **开喉剑** or some herbal throat lozenge — but I should focus on evidence-based options.\n\n3. For cough — if it's mild with small white sputum, may not need specific treatment. Could consider **右美沙芬** if cough is bothersome, but the complaint is mild.\n\nActually, let me look up some drugs to get their specifications and NRDL info.\n\nKey drugs to consider:\n- 对乙酰氨基酚 (paracetamol) for fever/pain\n- Maybe 布洛芬 (ibuprofen) as alternative\n- Maybe some cough medicine\n\nLet me also think about what to avoid:\n- Antibiotics (no bacterial infection evidence)\n- Moxifloxacin (previous adverse reaction - palpitations, QT risk)\n- Azithromycin (previous adverse reaction - palpitations, QT risk, combined with moxifloxacin was dangerous)\n- Any QT-prolonging drugs given the palpitation history\n\nLet me look up drug info for the medications I plan to prescribe.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0c9fa628-072c-4ed5-8a86-74d9418a1ac9","session_id":"a08d8111-c003-466b-97a2-5b924a979b4b"}
